{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"164711f9-52b3-4be6-a63a-795cade371f0","content":"Use **`dotnet run`**, not `dotnet test`.\n\nHot reload with `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.HotReload` requires running the test project directly:\n\n```bash\nDOTNET_WATCH_SUPPRESS_LAUNCH_BROWSER=1 dotnet watch run -- --hot-reload\n```\n\nOr simply:\n\n```bash\ndotnet run -- --hot-reload\n```\n\n**Why not `dotnet test`?** The `dotnet test` command manages the test host process itself and doesn't support the hot reload pipeline. Since your project has `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport` enabled, `dotnet run` will execute tests via the Microsoft Testing Platform directly, and the hot reload extension can hook into the file-watching loop to re-run tests on changes.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3c8a6789-874e-4340-9e56-ca76a74a83d6","outputTokens":179,"requestId":"042C:25FEDD:18E169A:1C603CE:69E8242B"},"id":"09d7a501-2153-46e8-8fbf-715e823d7c2a","timestamp":"2026-04-22T01:28:17.432Z","parentId":"0b26a84f-e4fc-43d5-b34c-e31dee4349e9"}
